== 3. f3 · Anti-Grünfeld ==
3. f3 is an Anti-Grünfeld move that was popularized by Alekhine.

It prepares e4 with a pawn to secure a big center. However, it weakens White's kingside and allows Black a larger lead in development. White usually castles queenside and starts a pawn storm on the kingside, similar to the '''[[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...Nf6/2. c4/2...g6/3. Nc3/3...Bg7/4. e4/4...d6/5. f3|Sämisch variation]]'''.

Black can choose to go into the mainline with '''[[/3...d5/]]''', playing in more of a Grünfeld fashion. Black is however free to go for one of the transpositional moves:

* '''[[/3...c5/]]''' transposes into a variation of the '''[[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...Nf6/2. c4/2...c5/3. d5/3...e6|Benoni defence]]''' where White has already played f3, eliminating some of White's usual options.
* '''[[/3...Bg7/]]''' and '''[[/3...d6/]]''' transpose into the '''[[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...Nf6/2. c4/2...g6/3. Nc3/3...Bg7/4. e4/4...d6/5. f3|Sämisch variation]]''' of the King's Indian.

Therefore, it is important for White to be comfortable in these openings as well if they want to avoid the Grünfeld with this move.

